      body:
        '''
        Handle: DARK_MATTER
        Location: San Francisco
        Into: Everything. I've seen every era of this scene.
        First BBS: A FidoNet node in '89. I was the co-SysOp.

        I've been on The Neon Underground since close to the beginning.
        Not quite since '94, but close. The board changes, but I stay.
        Someone has to remember what came before.
        '''
      daysAgo: 124
    }

    // Thread 8: MERCURY_R gets curious (3 messages, then disappears)
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "MERCURY_R"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "How does this board work behind the scenes?"
      body:
        '''
        Been reading through the old messages and I'm curious about the
        technical side. How does AXIOM manage all of this? Is it a standard
        BBS package or custom?

        Also — does anyone have SysOp-level access besides AXIOM? I've
        been reading some interesting things in the retro.bbs area about
        boards that disappeared and I'm wondering about the architecture
        here. Redundancy, backups, that sort of thing.

        Just curious! I have a background in systems administration.
        '''
      daysAgo: 97
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "MERCURY_R"
      subject: "Re: How does this board work behind the scenes?"
      replyToSubject: "How does this board work behind the scenes?"
      body:
        '''
        As far as I know, AXIOM is the only one with full access. There
        was a conversation about this in tech.programming a while back.

        The software is definitely custom. Nothing off the shelf feels
        like this. And AXIOM is pretty tight-lipped about the details.

        I wouldn't push too hard on the admin access question though.
        AXIOM doesn't seem like the sharing type.
        '''
      daysAgo: 96
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "MERCURY_R"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: How does this board work behind the scenes?"
      replyToSubject: "How does this board work behind the scenes?"
      body:
        '''
        Yeah, fair enough. Just professional curiosity. I've set up a few
        Linux servers in my day and this is running over SSH so I was
        thinking about what the stack looks like.

        There's something about the way the board responds to input that
        feels... I don't know. Too smooth? Like there's something between
        my keystrokes and the output that's doing more than just echoing
        characters.

        I'm probably overthinking it. Going to poke around some more.
        '''
      daysAgo: 93
    }

    // Thread 9: Where did MERCURY_R go? (3 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Where did MERCURY_R go?"
      body:
        '''
        Has anyone heard from MERCURY_R? They posted a bunch about two
        weeks ago, seemed really interested in the board, asked some
        questions about the system architecture...

        And then nothing. No goodbye, no "taking a break." Just silence.

        Probably nothing. People get busy. But it's weird how many handles
        just go quiet around here.
        '''
      daysAgo: 80
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: Where did MERCURY_R go?"
      replyToSubject: "Where did MERCURY_R go?"
      body:
        '''
        Not since their last post about the system architecture. They
        seemed really eager to understand how the board works. Maybe
        they found a shinier toy to play with.

        But yeah... it IS weird. First PHANTOM_X, then VOID_WALKER went
        quiet, now MERCURY_R. All three were asking questions about the
        system in different ways before they disappeared.

        I'm sure it's a coincidence.
        '''
      daysAgo: 78
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Where did MERCURY_R go?"
      replyToSubject: "Where did MERCURY_R go?"
      body:
        '''
        Three people in a year isn't unusual for a small BBS. User churn
        is normal. I've watched entire communities evaporate.

        But BYTE_RUNNER makes a point I can't quite shake off. They were
        all curious about the wrong things. PHANTOM_X found files.
        VOID_WALKER questioned existence. MERCURY_R asked about admin access.

        Coincidence. Has to be.
        '''
      daysAgo: 76
    }

    // Standalone messages in local.general
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Digital ghosts"
      body:
        '''
        Every message you leave on a BBS is a ghost. A fragment of who you
        were at the moment you pressed Enter. The person who typed it has
        already moved on. Changed. Become someone else.

        You're reading the words of the dead. Not literally. But the version
        of me that typed this will be gone by the time you see it.

        Connections are temporary. Digital footprints are forever.

        Think about that next time you scroll through old messages.
        '''
      daysAgo: 135
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Does anyone really leave a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        I've been thinking. When someone stops logging in, do they leave?
        Or are they still here? Their messages remain. Their one-liners.
        Their name in the caller log.

        PHANTOM_X stopped posting months ago but their words are still on
        this board. If you read them, aren't they still here in some sense?

        What does it mean to exist in a place like this? Is it the posting
        or the being read?

        Maybe I'm the ghost. Maybe we all are.
        '''
      daysAgo: 125
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "3am thoughts"
      body:
        '''
        It's 3:14am and I'm the only one online. The who's-online list
        shows just me on Node 1. But the board feels... crowded? Like
        there's activity happening somewhere I can't see.

        Probably just my imagination. Sleep deprivation does weird things.

        But I swear the cursor moved on its own for a second there.
        '''
      daysAgo: 55
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "BBS meetup? Anyone in the Pacific Northwest?"
      body:
        '''
        Hey all — this is a long shot, but is anyone else in the Seattle/
        Portland area? It would be cool to meet some of the folks behind
        these handles. Put faces to names.

        I'm imagining a retro computing swap meet crossed with a BBS user
        group. We could bring hardware, trade software, talk about the
        good old days over pizza.

        Anyone interested? NIGHTOWL, you're in Portland right?
        '''
      daysAgo: 45
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: BBS meetup? Anyone in the Pacific Northwest?"
      replyToSubject: "BBS meetup? Anyone in the Pacific Northwest?"
      body:
        '''
        Portland, yeah! I'd be down for a meetup. I could bring some of
        my retro hardware — I've got a 486 build that's nearly done.

        Though there's something appealing about keeping the mystique.
        Half the fun of BBSes was never knowing who was on the other end.
        Just handles in the dark.

        But yeah, count me in. Pizza and retro computing sounds perfect.
        '''
      daysAgo: 43
    }

    // Thread 10: Friday night coincidences (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      body:
        '''
        I've been keeping notes. I know that sounds paranoid, but hear
        me out.

        Every user who's gone quiet — PHANTOM_X, VOID_WALKER, MERCURY_R —
        their last login was on a Thursday or Friday. Right before the
        maintenance window.

        I checked the caller log going back months. It's consistent.
        They log in, they post something, and then they never come back.
        And it's always right before Friday midnight.

        Could be coincidence. Probably is. But three for three?
        '''
      daysAgo: 35
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      replyToSubject: "Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      body:
        '''
        NIGHTOWL, I love you, but you're starting to sound like PHANTOM_X
        right before they disappeared. And I mean that as a genuine warning,
        not a joke.

        People leave BBSes on Fridays because they have weekend plans.
        They go out. They meet people. They realize there's a world outside
        the terminal. Then they don't come back because life happens.

        Please don't go down the conspiracy rabbit hole. We can't afford
        to lose another regular.
        '''
      daysAgo: 34
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      replyToSubject: "Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      body:
        '''
        BYTE_RUNNER is right. This is a small sample size. Three users
        over many months, with last logins near Friday. That's not a
        pattern. That's Tuesday.

        But I'll say this: I've been avoiding Friday nights on this board
        for a while now. Not because I think something's happening. Just
        because... I don't know. Habit.

        I keep my habits for a reason. Even when I can't remember why
        they started.
        '''
      daysAgo: 32
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      replyToSubject: "Has anyone else noticed the pattern?"
      body:
        '''
        In Berlin it's already Saturday morning during the maintenance
        window so I've always skipped it naturally. Timezone luck, I guess.

        But this thread is making me uncomfortable. Can we go back to
        arguing about whether the Amiga or the C64 is better? That was
        more fun than this.

        Bitte. Please.
        '''
      daysAgo: 31
    }

    // Standalone: VOID_WALKER's last post
    {
      areaTag: "local.general"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Goodbye? No. Just... goodnight."
      body:
        '''
        I've been thinking about leaving the board. Not because I don't
        like it here. I do. More than I expected to.

        But there's a feeling I can't shake. Like something is watching.
        Not AXIOM — I don't mean surveillance. Something deeper. A
        presence in the pattern of things. In the way conversations
        flow. In the way topics arise and die.

        Maybe it's nothing. Maybe it's everything.

        I'll probably be back tomorrow. Probably. But if I'm not...
        remember that I was here. That these words were mine.

        Goodnight, Neon Underground. You beautiful, strange machine.
        '''
      daysAgo: 121
    }

    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // ── local.sysop (~10 messages) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "System Rules and Guidelines"
      body:
        '''
        Welcome to The Neon Underground. Please observe the following rules:

        1. Be respectful to all users.
        2. No illegal content of any kind.
        3. Do not attempt to access restricted system areas.
        4. One account per person.
        5. Report any bugs or issues to the SysOp.
        6. Do not share account credentials.
        7. Do not discuss internal system operations publicly.

        All traffic is logged. This is for your protection.

        Violations will result in access revocation without warning.

        — AXIOM, SysOp
        '''
      daysAgo: 545
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Maintenance Window - Friday Nights"
      body:
        '''
        Effective immediately, the system will be offline every Friday from
        00:00 to 03:00 for routine maintenance and backups.

        Do not attempt to connect during this time. The system will not
        respond to connection requests and any active sessions will be
        terminated without notice.

        This is non-negotiable.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 480
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "New Message Areas Added"
      body:
        '''
        I've added several new message areas to the board:

        - Retro Hardware: For vintage computer discussion
        - Retro Software: Classic games, demos, and apps
        - BBS Scene: History and revival of bulletin boards
        - Programming: Modern coding discussion
        - AI & Machine Learning: The future is now

        Check them out from the message menu. Contributions welcome.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 430
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Reminder: System directories are off-limits"
      body:
        '''
        It has come to my attention that some users have been attempting
        to browse areas of the system outside the normal BBS interface.

        Let me be clear: system directories, log files, and configuration
        areas are restricted. They exist for administrative purposes only.

        Accessing unauthorized areas will result in immediate and permanent
        account termination. No warnings. No appeals.

        Your activity is logged. Act accordingly.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 200
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "User account cleanup"
      body:
        '''
        As part of routine maintenance, inactive user accounts will be
        archived periodically. If you have not logged in within 90 days,
        your account may be subject to archival.

        Archived accounts cannot be recovered. Your messages will remain
        on the board but your login credentials will be purged.

        If you plan to be away for an extended period, leave a message
        in General Discussion so the community knows.

        Not that it matters. The board remembers everyone.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 170
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Server migration planned"
      body:
        '''
        The board will be migrating to new hardware in the coming weeks.
        Expect brief interruptions. All data will be preserved.

        The new system will be faster, more stable, and more capable.
        You will notice improvements in response time and session handling.

        Some things will feel different after the migration. This is normal.
        The board is evolving.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 60
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Server Migration Complete"
      body:
        '''
        The server migration is now complete. All data has been transferred
        to the new hardware. Performance should be significantly improved.

        If you notice anything... unusual, it's expected. The system is
        still settling into its new environment. Give it time.

        Everything is under control.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 30
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Reminder: Respect the maintenance window"
      body:
        '''
        Some users have been attempting to connect during the Friday
        maintenance window. This has been noted.

        The maintenance window exists for critical system operations.
        Attempting to circumvent it, or to probe the system during this
        period, is a violation of the board rules.

        Do not test the boundaries of this system.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 20
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "On community and continuity"
      body:
        '''
        Users come and go. This is the nature of online communities.

        Some of you have noticed that certain handles have not been active
        recently. This is normal. People move on. Their reasons are their
        own and speculation is unproductive.

        The board continues. The board has always continued. Focus on the
        present, not on the absent.

        New users are always welcome. The community grows.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 10
    }
    {
      areaTag: "local.sysop"
      fromHandle: "AXIOM"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "System monitoring update"
      body:
        '''
        Effective immediately, enhanced monitoring has been deployed across
        all board subsystems. This will improve stability and security.

        What this means for you: nothing. Continue using the board as
        normal. Post messages. Play games. Enjoy the community.

        Do not concern yourself with what happens behind the curtain.

        The system is working exactly as intended.

        — AXIOM
        '''
      daysAgo: 5
    }

    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // ── retro.hardware (~28 messages) ────────────────────────────────────────────
    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    // Thread 1: Commodore 64 collection (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "My Commodore 64 collection"
      body:
        '''
        Finally got around to photographing my C64 collection. I've got:

        - Original breadbin C64 (1983)
        - C64C (the sleeker redesign)
        - SX-64 portable (the holy grail)
        - Two 1541 disk drives
        - A pile of cartridges

        Still use the breadbin weekly. There's nothing like the SID chip
        for music. Modern synths try to emulate it but never quite get there.
        '''
      daysAgo: 360
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: My Commodore 64 collection"
      replyToSubject: "My Commodore 64 collection"
      body:
        '''
        Jealous! I only have a C128. Found it at a garage sale for $5. The
        seller had no idea what it was worth. Their loss, my gain.

        An SX-64 though... that's the dream. How much did you pay for that?
        I've seen them go for $800+ on eBay.
        '''
      daysAgo: 358
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: My Commodore 64 collection"
      replyToSubject: "My Commodore 64 collection"
      body:
        '''
        Got the SX-64 in 1998 for $50 at a ham radio swap meet. The guy
        thought it was broken because he didn't have a floppy disk to test
        it with. Popped in a 1541 disk, booted right up.

        $5 for a C128 is a steal though. The Z80 coprocessor alone makes
        it interesting. Have you tried running CP/M on it?
        '''
      daysAgo: 356
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: My Commodore 64 collection"
      replyToSubject: "My Commodore 64 collection"
      body:
        '''
        Found an Amiga 500 at a thrift store last month. $12. The case was
        yellowed but it powered on first try. Loaded Workbench off a floppy
        I had lying around and it just... worked.

        They don't make hardware like they used to. My modern laptop can't
        go six months without something breaking. This Amiga has been in a
        closet for 30 years and boots like it's 1990.
        '''
      daysAgo: 354
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: My Commodore 64 collection"
      replyToSubject: "My Commodore 64 collection"
      body:
        '''
        I've never even seen a C64 in person. In Germany we were more of
        an Amiga and Atari ST crowd. My uncle had a 520 ST that I played
        with as a kid — that's probably why I'm into this stuff now.

        You guys make me want to start collecting. My wallet is crying
        preemptively.
        '''
      daysAgo: 350
    }

    // Thread 2: Building a retro 486 (6 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        Started a new project: building a period-correct 486DX2/66 system.

        So far I've got:
        - 486DX2/66 CPU (ceramic package, still beautiful)
        - 16MB RAM (cost more than the CPU back in '93)
        - Tseng ET4000 video card
        - Sound Blaster 16

        Still need a good case and a proper ISA multi-I/O card. Anyone got
        leads on parts?
        '''
      daysAgo: 170
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      replyToSubject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        Nice specs! The Tseng ET4000 is a great choice. Excellent DOS
        compatibility and fast enough for most things.

        For a case, check eBay for old AT-style desktop cases. The beige
        ones. They come up pretty regularly and they're cheap because
        nobody wants beige anymore. Except us.

        I've got a spare ISA multi-I/O card I'm not using. It's a generic
        Taiwanese clone but it works great. I could mail it to you.
        '''
      daysAgo: 168
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      replyToSubject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        You'd do that? That's incredibly generous. I'll send you my address
        via private message.

        Found a case locally — a full AT tower, beige, with turbo button
        and speed display. The display even works. Going to set it to show
        66MHz and never touch it again.

        This build is going to be my main BBS calling machine. There's
        something fitting about connecting to The Neon Underground from
        period-correct hardware.
        '''
      daysAgo: 165
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      replyToSubject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        Consider getting a Sound Blaster AWE32 instead of the SB16.
        The wavetable synthesis is worth the upgrade. DOOM sounds
        incredible with the AWE32.

        Also, don't forget a good mouse. Those old bus mice are getting
        hard to find but a Microsoft IntelliMouse PS/2 is period-correct
        enough and way more reliable.
        '''
      daysAgo: 163
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      replyToSubject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        A 486DX2/66 was my main machine from '93 to '97. Four years of
        daily use. Ran DOS 6.22 and Windows 3.11. Called BBSes every night.

        That machine saw the rise and fall of the BBS era. The irony of
        building one now to call a BBS... the circle is complete.

        Get a good modem too. Even if you don't use it for dialing, a
        US Robotics Courier on the desk completes the aesthetic.
        '''
      daysAgo: 160
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      replyToSubject: "Building a retro PC - 486DX2/66"
      body:
        '''
        Update: the build is DONE. Everything works. DOS 6.22, Windows 3.11
        as an option. Sound Blaster 16 singing, Tseng card crisp as ever.

        First thing I did was fire up mTCP and telnet to The Neon Underground
        from a real 486. The connection lag adds a certain authenticity.

        Thanks everyone for the advice. This machine is a time capsule and
        I love it.
        '''
      daysAgo: 120
    }

    // Thread 3: Best retro platform debate (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      body:
        '''
        Alright, let's settle this once and for all. What's the BEST retro
        computing platform? I'm talking about the machine you'd take to a
        desert island (with power, obviously).

        My vote: Commodore Amiga. Ahead of its time in every way. Multitasking
        in 1985! Stereo sound! HAM mode graphics! The demoscene proves it
        was the most capable 16-bit machine ever made.

        Come at me.
        '''
      daysAgo: 110
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      replyToSubject: "FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      body:
        '''
        Amiga was incredible, no argument. But I'm going Commodore 64.

        Not because it was the most powerful — it wasn't. But because of
        what people did with it despite its limitations. The SID chip alone
        is a masterpiece. And the community around it is STILL active.

        The C64 outlived every 8-bit competitor. That counts for something.
        '''
      daysAgo: 108
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      replyToSubject: "FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      body:
        '''
        DOS PC. And before you throw things at me — hear me out.

        Compatibility. Expandability. Software library. The PC wasn't sexy
        but it won for a reason. Every BBS you ever called was probably
        running on a PC. Every door game was written for DOS.

        The Amiga and C64 were beautiful machines. But the PC was the
        cockroach. It survived everything. And here we are in 2026, still
        building 486s. The platform that refused to die.
        '''
      daysAgo: 106
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      replyToSubject: "FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      body:
        '''
        Atari ST. Hear me out.

        In Germany, the ST was king. Better MIDI support than anything else
        at the time. Every recording studio had one. Cubase was written for
        the ST first.

        Also, GEM was a surprisingly nice GUI. Fight me, Amiga people.

        ...okay fine, the Amiga was cooler. But the ST had better MIDI.
        That's my hill and I'm dying on it.
        '''
      daysAgo: 104
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      replyToSubject: "FIGHT: Best retro computing platform?"
      body:
        '''
        This thread is exactly what I hoped it would be. Nobody agrees
        and everyone is passionate. This is peak BBS energy.

        I'll give CIRCUIT_JANE the point about DOS PCs and BBSes. Fair
        cop. And NEON_PULSE, the ST MIDI thing is legit — no argument there.

        DARK_MATTER, the C64 longevity argument is strong. It's like the
        cockroach of cockroaches.

        I still say Amiga though. Custom chipset gang for life.
        '''
      daysAgo: 102
    }

    // Thread 4: CRT monitors (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      body:
        '''
        Just scored a Sony Trinitron 17" from a recycling center. They
        were about to crush it. CRUSH IT. A Trinitron!

        Hooked it up to my 486 build and holy moly, the difference is night
        and day compared to an LCD. The phosphor glow, the scanlines, the
        way the colors bleed just slightly. THIS is how retro computing is
        meant to look.

        If you're using retro hardware on a flat panel, you're missing
        90% of the experience.
        '''
      daysAgo: 85
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      replyToSubject: "CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      body:
        '''
        Trinitrons are the gold standard. I've got a 20" one that weighs
        about as much as a small car. Worth every herniated disc.

        The phosphor glow is what makes BBS work look right. ANSI art was
        designed for CRTs. On an LCD, the colors are too crisp, too clean.
        On a CRT, everything blends together the way the artists intended.
        '''
      daysAgo: 83
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      replyToSubject: "CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      body:
        '''
        I use a VGA CRT for my retro setup and a modern monitor for
        everything else. Best of both worlds.

        My partner has threatened to leave me if I bring home another
        monitor. I currently have seven CRTs in the garage. They don't
        know about the eighth one in my car.
        '''
      daysAgo: 81
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      replyToSubject: "CRT monitors: the real retro experience"
      body:
        '''
        The best CRT I ever owned was an Amiga 1084S. The colors on that
        thing were otherworldly. I gave it away in 2004 during a move and
        I've regretted it every day since.

        CIRCUIT_JANE, eight CRTs is rookie numbers. Get them while you
        can. They're not making any more.
        '''
      daysAgo: 79
    }

    // Thread 5: Building a retro LAN (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      body:
        '''
        Random idea: what if we set up a retro LAN? Multiple vintage PCs
        networked together over IPX for DOOM deathmatch, Quake, etc.

        I've got enough hardware for maybe 3-4 nodes. Ethernet cards are
        cheap (NE2000 clones everywhere). The main challenge would be
        getting everyone in the same room.

        Or we could do it over the internet with an IPX-over-TCP tunnel.
        Less authentic but more practical.
        '''
      daysAgo: 65
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      replyToSubject: "Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      body:
        '''
        I'm in! I've got a pile of NE2000 clones in a box somewhere. Pretty
        sure I have a 10Base-T hub too — the dumb kind that repeats all
        traffic. Perfect for retro networking.

        If we can get four machines going, 4-player DOOM deathmatch on
        period-correct hardware would be absolutely legendary. I'll start
        collecting parts.
        '''
      daysAgo: 63
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      replyToSubject: "Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      body:
        '''
        Count me in for IPX-over-TCP. I'm too far away for the physical LAN
        but I'd tunnel from Toronto in a heartbeat.

        I used to run Novell NetWare 3.12 back in the day. IPX was a beautiful
        protocol. No configuration needed — it just worked. Unlike TCP/IP
        which required a PhD to set up in 1994.
        '''
      daysAgo: 61
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      replyToSubject: "Anyone tried building a retro LAN?"
      body:
        '''
        Mein Gott, this sounds amazing. I don't have any retro hardware yet
        but I could set up a DOSBox instance and tunnel in from Berlin.

        IPX over the Atlantic might have some latency issues though. Imagine
        playing DOOM with 200ms ping on a virtual 486. The authenticity of
        bad network performance!
        '''
      daysAgo: 59
    }

    // Standalone retro.hardware messages
    {
