      replyToSubject: "Estate sale jackpot!"
      body:
        '''
        A Tandy 1000 SX! Those are surprisingly capable machines. The
        Tandy graphics and sound modes made them better than a standard
        PC clone for gaming.

        Sierra games on a Tandy 1000 were the definitive experience.
        King's Quest with 16-color Tandy graphics and 3-voice sound.
        If you haven't tried it, you're missing out.

        $60 for all of that is criminal. Good criminal, but criminal.
        '''
      daysAgo: 37
    }

    // Thread 6: Modem nostalgia (3 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "The sound of the modem handshake"
      body:
        '''
        Close your eyes and listen. You can still hear it, can't you?

        The dial tone. The dialing. The ring. Then the screech — that
        beautiful, chaotic screech of two modems negotiating a connection.
        The higher the pitch, the faster the speed. 14.4k had a different
        sound than 28.8k. You could tell the speed by ear.

        And then silence. Connected. The cursor blinks. You're in.

        There has never been a more satisfying sound in computing. Fight
        me on this and you will lose.
        '''
      daysAgo: 250
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: The sound of the modem handshake"
      replyToSubject: "The sound of the modem handshake"
      body:
        '''
        I have a US Robotics Courier v.Everything sitting on my desk right
        now. Not connected to anything. Just there. For the aesthetic.

        Sometimes I pick up the phone and hold it to the modem and imagine
        the handshake. My therapist says this is fine. I'm not sure she
        fully understands.

        The progression from 2400 to 56k was the real tech revolution.
        Forget the internet — the modem speed race was everything.
        '''
      daysAgo: 248
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: The sound of the modem handshake"
      replyToSubject: "The sound of the modem handshake"
      body:
        '''
        There's a website that lets you listen to modem handshake sounds
        at different baud rates. I've fallen asleep to it more than once.

        The 56k V.90 handshake is the most complex — it sounds like two
        robots having an argument. The 300 baud handshake is just a gentle
        warble. Like a bird call.

        We went from birdsong to machine screaming in 20 years. Progress.
        '''
      daysAgo: 245
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.hardware"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Anyone running old hardware as a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        Curious — is anyone here actually running BBS software on vintage
        hardware? Like a real 386 or 486 with a modem pool?

        I know most modern BBSes run on Linux or Raspberry Pis, but there's
        something romantic about the real thing. The hum of the hard drive,
        the blinking modem lights...

        Would love to hear about anyone's setup. What does this board run
        on, anyway? AXIOM never says.
        '''
      daysAgo: 30
    }

