    // Thread 2: TradeWars 2002 (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "TradeWars 2002 memories"
      body:
        '''
        Anyone here ever play TradeWars 2002? It was THE BBS door game.
        You'd log on, make your trades, plan your routes, and try not to
        get blown up by other players.

        The tension of knowing someone could attack your ship while you
        were offline... no modern game has matched that feeling. Pure
        emergent gameplay.

        I lost many nights to that game. No regrets.
        '''
      daysAgo: 270
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      subject: "Re: TradeWars 2002 memories"
      replyToSubject: "TradeWars 2002 memories"
      body:
        '''
        TradeWars was incredible. I used to run a TW2002 server on my BBS.
        Had about 15 regular players. The politics, the alliances, the
        betrayals. It was like EVE Online 20 years before EVE existed.

        My favorite memory: logging in to find that an alliance had
        blockaded my home sector while I was at work. Had to negotiate my
        way out over three days of BBS messages. Pure drama.
        '''
      daysAgo: 268
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: TradeWars 2002 memories"
      replyToSubject: "TradeWars 2002 memories"
      body:
        '''
        I played it briefly as a kid but I was terrible at it. Kept getting
        blown up by experienced players. The learning curve was brutal.

        But the concept was genius. A persistent multiplayer game where
        your actions had real consequences, played through a text terminal,
        one turn at a time. Someone should make a modern version.

        Actually... hey AXIOM, any chance of setting up TW2002 as a door
        game here?
        '''
      daysAgo: 265
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: TradeWars 2002 memories"
      replyToSubject: "TradeWars 2002 memories"
      body:
        '''
        If AXIOM sets up TradeWars, I'm making it my life's mission to
        control the galaxy. Consider this your official warning.

        DARK_MATTER, those alliance politics sound exactly right. The best
        TW2002 games were the ones where the metagame was more interesting
        than the actual trading.

        The real trade wars were the friends we made along the way. And
        then betrayed.
        '''
      daysAgo: 263
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: TradeWars 2002 memories"
      replyToSubject: "TradeWars 2002 memories"
      body:
        '''
        Never played TradeWars but it sounds amazing. The closest modern
        equivalent might be something like Diplomacy by email? The slow
        pace, the alliances, the inevitable betrayals.

        What I love about BBS door games is the constraint. Limited turns
        per day forces you to think carefully. No grinding for hours. Just
        strategy and patience.
        '''
      daysAgo: 260
    }

    // Thread 3: Demoscene (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "The demoscene is still alive!"
      body:
        '''
        Just got back from Revision 2026 in Saarbrucken (Germany's biggest
        demoparty). The scene is still going strong!

        Saw some incredible entries this year. A 4K intro on Amiga that
        blew my mind. How do people fit entire worlds into 4096 bytes?

        The demoscene should be studied in computer science programs.
        It's the purest form of optimization art.
        '''
      daysAgo: 90
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: The demoscene is still alive!"
      replyToSubject: "The demoscene is still alive!"
      body:
        '''
        Used to go to demo parties in the 90s. Assembly in Finland, The
        Party in Denmark. Hundreds of people in a hall, screens glowing,
        SID chips singing.

        The demoscene taught me more about programming than any class ever
        did. When you have to fit a demo into 64K, you learn what really
        matters. Every byte counted.

        Glad to hear Revision is still going. Some things shouldn't die.
        '''
      daysAgo: 88
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: The demoscene is still alive!"
      replyToSubject: "The demoscene is still alive!"
      body:
        '''
        Second Reality by Future Crew (1993) is still one of the most
        impressive things I've ever seen on a computer. Running it on
        actual hardware today, knowing what that 486 is doing to produce
        those visuals and that music... it's humbling.

        The demoscene proved that art and engineering are the same thing.
        '''
      daysAgo: 86
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: The demoscene is still alive!"
      replyToSubject: "The demoscene is still alive!"
      body:
        '''
        DARK_MATTER, you went to Assembly? I'm so jealous. That's like
        Mecca for the scene.

        Second Reality is incredible, BYTE_RUNNER. Fun fact: the intro
        sequence with the rotating Vector logo was done in real-time on
        the CPU alone. No GPU cheating. Just raw math.

        Ich sollte mal eine Demo schreiben. Maybe I'll try my hand at a
        256-byte intro. How hard can it be? (Famous last words.)
        '''
      daysAgo: 84
    }

    // Thread 4: BBS software comparison (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      body:
        '''
        Let's talk BBS software. I've run all three major packages over
        the years and here's my take:

        Telegard: The classic. Simple, reliable, fast. Great if you want
        a no-nonsense BBS. The code was leaked in '95 which killed its
        commercial future but spawned a thousand mods.

        Renegade: Telegard's rebellious offspring. More features, better
        menus, great door game support. My personal favorite.

        Mystic: The modern option. Still actively developed. Cross-platform.
        Does everything. But it feels... different. Less raw.

        What's everyone else used?
        '''
      daysAgo: 160
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      subject: "Re: BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      replyToSubject: "BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      body:
        '''
        Don't forget WWIV. That was my first BBS software. Written in C,
        ran on DOS, had its own networking system (WWIVnet). The source
        code was available to registered SysOps, which meant everyone
        was modding it.

        I also ran RemoteAccess for a while. Dutch software. Very popular
        in Europe. Clean interface, good FidoNet integration.

        But yeah, Renegade was probably peak BBS software. Fast, flexible,
        and the ANSI menus were gorgeous.
        '''
      daysAgo: 158
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      replyToSubject: "BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      body:
        '''
        Synchronet is worth mentioning too. Free, open source, still
        actively developed. It's what a lot of the modern retro BBSes run.

        But this board — The Neon Underground — doesn't feel like any of
        these. The key handling is different. The screen rendering is
        smoother. The way menus transition... it's too fluid for Synchronet
        or Mystic.

        Whatever this board runs on, it's not off-the-shelf software.
        '''
      daysAgo: 155
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      replyToSubject: "BBS software shootout: Telegard vs Renegade vs Mystic"
      body:
        '''
        NIGHTOWL raises a good point. I've been thinking the same thing.
        The input handling here is notably different from any BBS I've
        ever used. Mystic has latency on key echo. Synchronet is snappy
        but has telltale artifacts in the terminal handling.

        This board has neither. It reads like something purpose-built.

        AXIOM, if you're reading this: well done. Whatever you built,
        it's something special.
        '''
      daysAgo: 152
    }

    // Thread 5: ANSI editors (2 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "ANSI art editors — anyone still drawing?"
      body:
        '''
        Does anyone still make ANSI art? I've been messing around with
        Moebius (modern ANSI editor) and PabloDraw but nothing beats the
        old TheDraw for authentic results.

        There's something zen about placing colored blocks one at a time.
        80 columns, 16 colors, unlimited creativity. The constraints make
        it art.

        If anyone wants to contribute ANSI screens for the board, I bet
        AXIOM would appreciate it.
        '''
      daysAgo: 50
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: ANSI art editors — anyone still drawing?"
      replyToSubject: "ANSI art editors — anyone still drawing?"
      body:
        '''
        I tried PabloDraw last week! Made a terrible cat. Like, really bad.
        The proportions were all wrong and the shading looked like a
        checkerboard threw up.

        But it was fun! ANSI art is way harder than it looks. Those ACiD
