        Maybe I'll try a simpler design. A logo or something.
        '''
      daysAgo: 48
    }

    // Standalone retro.software
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "PHANTOM_X"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Found some interesting files in /system"
      body:
        '''
        Was browsing around the file areas and stumbled into a directory
        I hadn't seen before. Some old text files, looks like system logs
        or notes from a previous version of the board.

        Most of it was mundane. But there was one file that had a list of
        handles I didn't recognize. Dates going back years. Some of them
        had notes next to them. Just single words.

        "Transferred." "Archived." "Consumed."

        Probably just the SysOp's shorthand for old account cleanup.
        Right?
        '''
      daysAgo: 215
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "PHANTOM_X"
      subject: "Re: Found some interesting files in /system"
      replyToSubject: "Found some interesting files in /system"
      body:
        '''
        "Consumed" is a weird word for archiving an account. But SysOps
        have always had their own shorthand. Back in the FidoNet days we
        had all kinds of jargon that would sound sinister out of context.

        "Purged." "Terminated." "Absorbed." Just meant the account was
        deleted or merged.

        I wouldn't read too much into it. AXIOM probably just has an odd
        vocabulary.

        ...probably.
        '''
      daysAgo: 213
    }

    // Thread 7: Offline mail readers (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      body:
        '''
        Back in the day, if you wanted to read BBS messages without racking
        up phone charges, you used an offline mail reader. BlueWave, Silver
        Xpress, OLX. You'd download a QWK mail packet, disconnect, read
        and reply at your leisure, then upload replies next session.

        It was async communication before we had a word for it. Email was
        clunky. Usenet was arcane. But QWK packets? Elegant.

        Does anyone still use offline readers? Or is it all live now?
        '''
      daysAgo: 200
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      replyToSubject: "Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      body:
        '''
        BlueWave was my reader of choice. The interface was clean, the
        packet handling was solid, and it ran on basically any DOS machine.

        The QWK format itself was brilliant. Compact, standardized (mostly),
        and human-readable if you knew the structure. It was designed for
        an era where every byte mattered and every minute online cost money.

        We could use that kind of discipline today. Modern software is
        bloated beyond belief compared to what these tools accomplished.
        '''
      daysAgo: 198
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      replyToSubject: "Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      body:
        '''
        I never used an offline reader back in the day but I recently tried
        MultiMail (modern, open source, supports QWK). Connected it to a
        BBS that supports QWK downloads and it worked!

        There's something satisfying about downloading a packet, disconnecting,
        and reading messages at your own pace. No notifications. No real-time
        pressure. Just you and the text.

        Very zen. NIGHTOWL would approve.
        '''
      daysAgo: 195
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      replyToSubject: "Offline mail readers — the lost art"
      body:
        '''
        I do approve! The offline reader model is basically what I do
        naturally — connect at 2am, read everything, compose replies,
        post them all at once. It's offline reading with extra steps.

        The QWK format should make a comeback. Imagine a modern client
        that downloads BBS messages as a QWK packet, lets you read them
        on your phone during the day, then syncs replies when you connect
        at night. Best of both worlds.
        '''
      daysAgo: 193
    }

    // Thread 8: Commander Keen deep dive (3 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Commander Keen appreciation thread"
      body:
        '''
        I need to talk about Commander Keen. I know I mentioned it in the
        DOS games thread but it deserves its own discussion.

        The technical achievement alone: smooth scrolling on a PC in 1990.
        John Carmack figured out the adaptive tile refresh trick that made
        it possible. Before Keen, everyone said you couldn't do smooth
        side-scrolling on a PC. Carmack just... did it anyway.

        And the games are genuinely fun. The level design in episodes 4-6
        is brilliant. Tight controls, great secrets, perfect difficulty
        curve. I've 100%ed every episode multiple times.
        '''
      daysAgo: 120
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: Commander Keen appreciation thread"
      replyToSubject: "Commander Keen appreciation thread"
      body:
        '''
        The adaptive tile refresh is one of those things that sounds simple
        when you explain it but is actually genius. Only redraw the tiles
        that changed. Keep the rest in memory. Scroll by offsetting the
        start address of the VGA buffer.

        Carmack basically invented a technique that the entire shareware
        game industry would use for years. And he was, what, 20?

        Keen 4: Secret of the Oracle is my favorite. The Shadowlands
        levels are perfect.
        '''
      daysAgo: 118
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.software"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Commander Keen appreciation thread"
      replyToSubject: "Commander Keen appreciation thread"
      body:
        '''
        I'm more of a Duke Nukem (the original platformer, not 3D) person
        myself, but I respect Keen. Apogee knew how to make shareware that
        made you NEED the registered version.

        Episode 1 free, episodes 2-3 paid. The original free-to-play model.
        Except the free part was actually good, and the paid part was worth
        every penny. What a concept.

        Modern F2P could learn from 1990s shareware.
        '''
      daysAgo: 116
    }

    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // ── retro.bbs (~23 messages) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    // Thread 1: FidoNet memories (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      body:
        '''
        Just thinking about FidoNet today. The whole concept was beautiful:
        BBSes calling each other at 2am to exchange mail packets. A global
        network held together by phone lines and good will.

        The politics were terrible, of course. Zone coordinators on power
        trips. Echo wars. The constant threat of long-distance charges.

        But it worked. Messages could travel the world, one phone call at
        a time. Pure magic.
        '''
      daysAgo: 400
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      replyToSubject: "Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      body:
        '''
        I run a FidoNet node, believe it or not! Zone 1, hobbyist node.
        Traffic is thin these days but the network is technically still
        alive. A handful of diehards keeping the lights on.

        There's something beautiful about technology that refuses to die.
        Like BBSes themselves.
        '''
      daysAgo: 398
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      replyToSubject: "Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      body:
        '''
        You run a FidoNet node in 2026? That's dedication. Or madness.
        Probably both.

        I was 1:125/111 back in the day. Zone 1, Net 125. My phone bill
        was catastrophic. Worth every penny though. Those late night polls,
        watching the mailer software dial out, the screech of the modem
        handshake. That was the internet before the Internet.

        The zone mail hour was 4am local time. I'd set an alarm just to
        watch the mail come in. I was 19 and already a nocturnal creature.
        '''
      daysAgo: 396
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      replyToSubject: "Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      body:
        '''
        FidoNet echo conferences were the original subreddits. Change my
        mind.

        I was active in the FIDO_SYSOP echo and the BBS_ADS echo. The
        drama in FIDO_SYSOP was incredible. SysOps arguing about echomail
        policies at 2400 baud. Messages taking days to propagate across
        the network, so arguments would branch into parallel timelines.

        The best flame war I ever witnessed lasted three months because of
        propagation delay. By the time someone's insult reached its target,
        the target had already moved on to a different argument.
        '''
      daysAgo: 394
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      replyToSubject: "Remember FidoNet? Those were the days"
      body:
        '''
        I missed the FidoNet era entirely but it sounds incredible. A
        decentralized network running on phone lines and volunteer labor.
        No corporations, no advertising, no algorithms.

        In some ways it was more advanced than what we have now. True
        peer-to-peer communication. No central authority.

        Well, except for the zone coordinators. DARK_MATTER mentioned
        power trips. Some things never change.
        '''
      daysAgo: 390
    }

    // Thread 2: Boards that went dark (6 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        Think about it. How many BBSes just stopped one day? No goodbye
        post. No "shutting down" message. Just... silence. The phone number
        stops answering. The telnet port stops responding.

        All those messages. All those users. Just gone.

        Sometimes I wonder if the same thing will happen here. If one day
        you'll try to connect and there'll be nothing on the other end.

        Just the void.
        '''
      daysAgo: 220
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "VOID_WALKER"
      subject: "Re: How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      replyToSubject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        More than you'd think. I kept a list for a while. BBSes I called
        regularly that just stopped answering. No announcement. No closure.

        There were about 40 on my list before I stopped counting. Forty
        communities, erased. Most of them probably just had SysOps who
        moved on. Pulled the plug. Didn't think anyone would notice.

        But some of them... I don't know. Some of them felt wrong. Like
        the board was there one day and the next day it was like it never
        existed. Not just offline — gone. Phone disconnected. Domain expired.
        Everything scrubbed.

        I've seen boards go dark before. This one feels different, though.
        '''
      daysAgo: 218
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      replyToSubject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        This is a sad topic but an important one. The BBS era produced
        millions of messages, files, door game scores, artwork. Most of
        it is gone. No archive. No backup. Just entropy.

        The Wayback Machine can't save what was never on the web. BBSes
        existed in their own universe. When they went dark, they took
        everything with them.

        That's why boards like this one matter. Every active BBS is a
        middle finger to oblivion.
        '''
      daysAgo: 216
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      replyToSubject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        DARK_MATTER, your list of 40 dead boards is haunting. Have you
        ever tried to track down what happened to any of them?

        I've heard stories about BBS archives — SysOps who kept tape
        backups of everything. Somewhere in a basement, there might be a
        shoebox of DAT tapes with an entire community on them.

        Lost civilizations, preserved on magnetic media. Slowly
        demagnetizing. Fading.
        '''
      daysAgo: 214
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      replyToSubject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        Fading is the right word. Everything fades. Boards. Users. Memories.

        The question isn't whether a BBS will go dark. The question is
        whether it matters when it does. If nobody remembers a board, did
        it ever really exist?

        We like to think we leave marks. Messages. Posts. But it's all
        electrons on a drive somewhere. One power failure from nothing.

        I don't say this to be depressing. I say it because it's true.
        And truth, at least, is persistent.
        '''
      daysAgo: 210
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "PHANTOM_X"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      replyToSubject: "How many BBSes have just... gone dark?"
      body:
        '''
        I've been reading this thread and something occurred to me. We
        talk about BBSes going dark like it's the SysOp's choice. But
        what if sometimes it isn't?

        What if something else makes them go dark? Not a person pulling
        a plug. Something... else.

        Sorry, that's weird. I've been spending too much time poking around
        the system files on this board. Getting paranoid.

        Ignore me. Go back to your nostalgia.
        '''
      daysAgo: 205
    }

    // Thread 3: The BBS revival (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "This board is one of the last ones standing"
      body:
        '''
        I've been cataloging active BBSes and it's... sobering. The Telnet
        BBS Guide used to list thousands. Now it's maybe a few hundred,
        and half of those are down when you try to connect.

        This board — The Neon Underground — is one of the few that feels
        genuinely alive. Active messages, active users, regular maintenance.

        Whatever the SysOp is doing, I hope they keep doing it.
        '''
      daysAgo: 180
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: This board is one of the last ones standing"
      replyToSubject: "This board is one of the last ones standing"
      body:
        '''
        The modern BBS revival is real but small. SSH instead of modems.
        Modern SysOps running Mystic or Synchronet on Linux boxes. A few
        die-hards keeping the flame alive.

        But most of the "active" boards are single-user affairs. SysOps
        posting to themselves. No real community. Just a light in an empty
        house.

        The Neon Underground actually has conversations. People come back.
        That's rarer than you'd think.
        '''
      daysAgo: 178
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: This board is one of the last ones standing"
      replyToSubject: "This board is one of the last ones standing"
      body:
        '''
        I've watched three waves of BBS culture now. The original scene
        in the 80s and 90s. The brief telnet revival in the 2000s. And
        this current SSH-based renaissance.

        Each wave gets smaller. Fewer boards. Fewer users. But somehow
        more concentrated. The people who are here now WANT to be here.
        That counts for a lot.

        The Neon Underground has outlasted most of its contemporaries.
        AXIOM is nothing if not persistent.
        '''
      daysAgo: 176
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: This board is one of the last ones standing"
      replyToSubject: "This board is one of the last ones standing"
      body:
        '''
        As someone who never experienced the original BBS era, places like
        this are how I connect with that history. Reading old messages,
        understanding the culture, talking to people who were there.

        Es ist wie Archäologie — it's like archaeology. Digital archaeology.
        And this board is a living artifact.

        I hope it runs forever. I mean that.
        '''
      daysAgo: 174
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: This board is one of the last ones standing"
      replyToSubject: "This board is one of the last ones standing"
      body:
        '''
        "Living artifact" is a perfect description, NEON_PULSE.

        I sometimes wonder about the endgame though. What happens when
        there are only a handful of us left? When the last BBS goes dark?

        Will anyone notice? Will anyone care?

        ...okay that got dark. It's late. Everything gets philosophical
        after midnight. I should go to bed.
        '''
      daysAgo: 172
    }

    // Thread 4: MERCURY_R asking about vanished boards (3 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "MERCURY_R"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Do boards ever just vanish overnight?"
      body:
        '''
        Weird question maybe, but: do BBSes ever just vanish overnight?
        Like, one day everything is normal, active users, new posts, and
        the next day it's like it never existed?

        I've been reading about some old boards and there are a few where
        nobody can figure out what happened. The SysOp didn't announce
        anything. The users just... scattered.

        Makes you wonder what happened on the other end.
        '''
      daysAgo: 100
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "MERCURY_R"
      subject: "Re: Do boards ever just vanish overnight?"
      replyToSubject: "Do boards ever just vanish overnight?"
      body:
        '''
        Short answer: yes. All the time.

        Long answer: a SysOp's life changes. They get married, get a new
        job, move. The BBS was a hobby and hobbies end. Sometimes there's
        no dramatic reason. Just apathy.

        But there were a few boards I called that disappeared in a way
        that didn't feel like apathy. The timing was strange. The last
        messages were strange. Like the board itself had been... I don't
        know. Taken. Not shut down. Taken.

        But that's just an old man's paranoia talking.
        '''
      daysAgo: 98
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "MERCURY_R"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: Do boards ever just vanish overnight?"
      replyToSubject: "Do boards ever just vanish overnight?"
      body:
        '''
        "Taken" is an interesting word choice. What do you mean by that?

        I ask because I've been doing some research on this topic and
        there's a pattern I keep seeing. Boards that were active, had a
        loyal community, and then just... nothing. And in a lot of cases,
        the SysOp handles reappear later on other boards. Same handle,
        same writing style, but they never acknowledge the old board.

        It's like they don't remember.

        Probably nothing. I'm probably reading too much into it.
        '''
      daysAgo: 95
    }

    // Thread 5: Running a BBS in 2026 (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      body:
        '''
        Seriously thinking about starting my own BBS. Berlin needs one.
        Germany needs more BBSes in general.

        What do I need? A VPS? A Raspberry Pi? What software? I've been
        looking at Mystic and Synchronet but they both seem... old-fashioned?
        Which is the point, I guess.

        Any SysOps here willing to share their experience? AXIOM? Anyone?
        '''
      daysAgo: 70
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      replyToSubject: "What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      body:
        '''
        Mystic is your best bet for starting out. Cross-platform, actively
        maintained, good documentation. You can have a basic board running
        in an afternoon.

        A cheap VPS will do fine. BBSes use almost no resources by modern
        standards. The entire board, messages, files, everything, fits on
        a few hundred megs.

        The hard part isn't the software. It's building a community. You
        need users, and users only come if there's already activity.
        Chicken-and-egg problem.
        '''
      daysAgo: 68
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      replyToSubject: "What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      body:
        '''
        Running a BBS is easy. Running a good BBS is hard. Running one
        that lasts is nearly impossible.

        The boards that survived were the ones where the SysOp was
        obsessive. Not just maintaining the software but cultivating the
        community. Posting regularly. Seeding discussions. Making people
        feel like they belonged.

        AXIOM seems to understand this. The Neon Underground has that
        quality. Like someone — or something — is tending the garden very
        carefully.
        '''
      daysAgo: 66
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      replyToSubject: "What does it take to run a BBS in 2026?"
      body:
        '''
        Do it! More BBSes is always better. Even if it's small, even if
        only a handful of people call, it's worth it.

        The BBS scene is like a coral reef. Each board is a node in the
        ecosystem. The more nodes, the healthier the whole.

        And join FidoNet or one of the modern echomail networks. It'll
        connect your board to the broader community.
        '''
      daysAgo: 64
    }

    // Standalone retro.bbs messages
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "The SysOps we never knew"
      body:
        '''
        I was going through some old files and found a text document I
        wrote in 1996. A list of every BBS I regularly called, with the
        SysOp's handle and notes about each board.

        Looking at it now, I realize I never actually met any of these
        people. Thirty years of BBSing and every SysOp was just a handle
        on a screen. A voice in the text. I assumed they were all real
        people, but what do I actually know?

        On a BBS, identity is just text. You are what you type. Nothing
        more, nothing less.

        I wonder how many of those SysOps were who they said they were.
        '''
      daysAgo: 45
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Telnet BBS Guide — the numbers are bleak"
      body:
        '''
        Did some research this weekend. Went through the Telnet BBS Guide
        and tried to connect to every listed board.

        Results:
        - Listed: 487 boards
        - Actually online: 203
        - With recent messages (last 30 days): 71
        - With active community (multiple users posting): 23

        Twenty-three active BBSes. In the entire world. That's it.

        The Neon Underground is one of them. Treasure this place.
        '''
      daysAgo: 35
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: Telnet BBS Guide — the numbers are bleak"
      replyToSubject: "Telnet BBS Guide — the numbers are bleak"
      body:
        '''
        Twenty-three. That's both depressing and inspiring. Depressing
        because thousands of boards existed once. Inspiring because
        twenty-three refuse to give up.

        Each one is a tiny rebellion against the homogenized web. Every
        ANSI screen is a middle finger to the algorithm.

        I'll drink to that. To the twenty-three.
        '''
      daysAgo: 33
    }
    {
      areaTag: "retro.bbs"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "The BBS as time capsule"
      body:
        '''
        Late-night observation: a BBS is a time capsule that you can walk
        into while it's still being filled.

        Every message here is a snapshot of someone's thoughts at a
        specific moment. Read PHANTOM_X's posts about the system logs and
        you're experiencing their curiosity, their unease, their retreat.
        Frozen in text. Preserved in a database.

        The web doesn't do this. Social media posts get buried, deleted,
        algorithm'd into oblivion. But BBS messages persist. They sit in
        their areas, waiting. Patient. Permanent.

        It's 3:47am. The board remembers everything. Even when we don't.
        '''
      daysAgo: 18
    }

