    // Thread 1: Learning Rust (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      body:
        '''
        Started learning Rust last week. The borrow checker is kicking my
        ass but I'm starting to see why people love it. Memory safety
        without a garbage collector is pretty elegant.

        Wrote a simple CLI tool that converts pipe codes to ANSI. Took
        way longer than it should have because of lifetime annotations.

        Anyone else here into Rust? Would love to swap notes.
        '''
      daysAgo: 165
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      replyToSubject: "Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      body:
        '''
        Started with it last month! The learning curve is steep but worth it.
        I'm building a small CLI tool to manage my retro hardware inventory.

        Pro tip: don't fight the borrow checker. Work with it. Once it
        clicks, you'll wonder how you ever lived without it.

        Also, the Rust community is incredibly helpful. The subreddit and
        Discord are full of patient people. Unlike some other language
        communities I won't name.
        '''
      daysAgo: 163
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      replyToSubject: "Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      body:
        '''
        A hardware inventory tool in Rust sounds fun! Are you using a
        database or just flat files?

        I've been reading the Rust Book (online, free) and it's genuinely
        one of the best programming tutorials I've ever read. The chapter
        on ownership made something click in my brain.

        Endlich verstehe ich Speicherverwaltung! Finally understanding
        memory management after years of Python and JS.
        '''
      daysAgo: 161
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      replyToSubject: "Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      body:
        '''
        I looked at Rust once. Then I looked at the borrow checker. Then
        I closed the tab and went back to Python.

        Kidding. Mostly. I respect Rust but at my age I've earned the right
        to use garbage-collected languages. Life's too short for lifetime
        annotations.

        But good on you two for learning it. The BBS scene needs more
        modern tools.
        '''
      daysAgo: 158
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      replyToSubject: "Learning Rust - anyone else?"
      body:
        '''
        I've programmed in C, C++, Pascal, Perl, Python, Ruby, Go, and
        now Rust. Every language is a lens. Each one shows you something
        different about what a program can be.

        Rust shows you that safety and performance aren't enemies. That's
        a valuable lesson. Even if the syntax makes my eyes water.

        NEON_PULSE, keep at it. The borrow checker pain is temporary.
        The understanding is permanent.
        '''
      daysAgo: 155
    }

    // Thread 2: What's this board written in? (5 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "What language was this BBS written in?"
      body:
        '''
        Does anyone know what The Neon Underground is built with? The
        terminal handling is really smooth. Way better than most BBS
        software I've seen.

        It doesn't feel like Synchronet or Mystic. Custom job maybe?

        @AXIOM, care to share? :)
        '''
      daysAgo: 130
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      subject: "Re: What language was this BBS written in?"
      replyToSubject: "What language was this BBS written in?"
      body:
        '''
        My guess is TypeScript or maybe Go. The session handling feels
        too modern for C. And the SSH layer is definitely custom — no
        standard BBS package does SSH natively like this.

        The way it handles terminal escape sequences is really clean too.
        Someone who understood VT100 at a deep level wrote this.
        '''
      daysAgo: 128
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What language was this BBS written in?"
      replyToSubject: "What language was this BBS written in?"
      body:
        '''
        TypeScript would make sense! SSH via Node.js is totally doable
        with the ssh2 library. And the UI feels like something built with
        a reactive framework — the way screens transition and state is
        managed.

        If AXIOM wrote this from scratch in TypeScript, that's seriously
        impressive. A full BBS with ANSI rendering, message threading,
        door games, user auth... that's a LOT of code.

        Respekt, AXIOM. Respect.
        '''
      daysAgo: 126
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What language was this BBS written in?"
      replyToSubject: "What language was this BBS written in?"
      body:
        '''
        Been thinking about CIRCUIT_JANE's question. This board has
        features I've never seen on any other BBS. The way the menus work,
        the message threading, the screen rendering...

        AXIOM must be quite the coder. Or quite the... something.
        I've never met AXIOM in person. Has anyone? Does anyone even know
        who they are? In all the years I've been here, AXIOM has never
        slipped. Never revealed anything personal. Not a location, not a
        timezone, not a gender.

        Just "AXIOM." Since 1994.
        '''
      daysAgo: 124
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "DARK_MATTER"
      subject: "Re: What language was this BBS written in?"
      replyToSubject: "What language was this BBS written in?"
      body:
        '''
        The same handle since 1994 isn't that unusual. I've kept mine for
        30 years. But DARK_MATTER raises a good point — we know literally
        nothing about AXIOM beyond the handle and the title "SysOp."

        Location: Unknown. That's what the user list says. Not "withheld"
        or "private." Unknown. Like even the system doesn't know.

        I asked AXIOM directly once via private message about the software
        stack. The reply was just: "The board runs on what it needs to run
        on." Helpful.
        '''
      daysAgo: 122
    }

    // Thread 3: Python vs TypeScript (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      body:
        '''
        I've been going back and forth between Python and TypeScript for
        my side projects. Python is faster to prototype but TypeScript
        catches more bugs at compile time.

        For a BBS-related tool (like an offline mail reader), which would
        you pick? I'm leaning TypeScript since this board might be built
        with it.

        Was meint ihr? What do you all think?
        '''
      daysAgo: 75
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      replyToSubject: "Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      body:
        '''
        TypeScript, no question. The type system saves you from yourself.
        I've lost hours to Python runtime errors that TypeScript would
        have caught instantly.

        Plus, if you're building BBS tools, Node.js has great terminal
        handling libraries. Blessed, ink, and the raw ANSI escape code
        stuff. Python can do it too but it's clunkier.
        '''
      daysAgo: 73
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      replyToSubject: "Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      body:
        '''
        Python. Because I'm old and I don't want to deal with node_modules.

        Seriously though, for quick tools and scripts, Python wins on
        simplicity. For anything that needs to handle async I/O heavily
        (like, say, a BBS), TypeScript on Node is hard to beat.

        Use both. They're tools, not religions.
        '''
      daysAgo: 71
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      replyToSubject: "Python vs TypeScript for side projects?"
      body:
        '''
        "They're tools, not religions." CIRCUIT_JANE, I'm putting that on
        a t-shirt.

        Going with TypeScript for the offline reader. I'll share the code
        here when it's ready. Open source, of course. Maybe it'll be
        useful for other boards too.

        Thanks for the input everyone!
        '''
      daysAgo: 69
    }

    // Standalone tech.programming messages
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "The beauty of terminal UIs"
      body:
        '''
        3am coding session. Been building a TUI (terminal user interface)
        for a personal project and I'm falling in love with the constraints.

        80 columns. 24 rows. 16 colors. No mouse. No animations. No
        JavaScript framework of the week. Just text, intelligently placed.

        Every pixel — sorry, every character cell — matters in a TUI. You
        can't waste space. You can't distract with flashy visuals. The
        information has to be clear, or the interface fails.

        Modern UI designers could learn a lot from BBS screens.
        '''
      daysAgo: 35
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: The beauty of terminal UIs"
      replyToSubject: "The beauty of terminal UIs"
      body:
        '''
        Couldn't agree more. There's a reason TUIs are having a renaissance
        right now. lazygit, btop, ranger — people are rediscovering that
        the terminal is a perfectly valid UI paradigm.

        The best TUIs I've ever used were BBS menus. Instant response,
        clear navigation, zero ambiguity about what each key does. Every
        modern web app could learn from ANSI menus.
        '''
      daysAgo: 33
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "I automated my coffee machine with TypeScript"
      body:
        '''
        This is only tangentially programming-related but I had to share.

        My espresso machine has a serial port (don't ask). I wrote a
        TypeScript script that connects to it, reads the temperature
        sensor, and sends me a notification when it's ready.

        Next step: integrate it with the BBS. Type a command, and coffee
        starts brewing 4,800 miles away in Berlin.

        Das ist die Zukunft. This is the future.
        '''
      daysAgo: 15
    }

    // Thread 5: Git and version control (3 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "How did we survive before version control?"
      body:
        '''
        I was organizing some old project folders and found about 15 copies
        of the same program:

        game.c
        game_v2.c
        game_FINAL.c
        game_FINAL_REAL.c
        game_FINAL_REAL_v2_USE_THIS_ONE.c

        How did we live like this? Git has spoiled me completely. The idea
        of making backups by copying folders gives me anxiety now.

        I wonder what AXIOM uses for version control on this board. Or if
        the code just springs into existence fully formed. Wouldn't surprise me.
        '''
      daysAgo: 50
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: How did we survive before version control?"
      replyToSubject: "How did we survive before version control?"
      body:
        '''
        I was a PVCS girl. Then CVS. Then Subversion. Then Git.

        Each one felt revolutionary at the time. PVCS let you lock files
        so two people couldn't edit at once. CVS let you merge changes.
        SVN gave you atomic commits. Git gave you distributed everything.

        But yeah, the "FINAL_REAL_v2" naming convention was the real MVP
        of the 90s. It somehow worked. Until it didn't.
        '''
      daysAgo: 48
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.programming"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: How did we survive before version control?"
      replyToSubject: "How did we survive before version control?"
      body:
        '''
        I literally cannot imagine programming without git. It's like
        asking how people navigated without GPS. They did, obviously,
        but the thought gives me vertigo.

        Fun fact: git was created by Linus Torvalds in 2005 because he
        was annoyed with every existing version control system. So he
        wrote his own. In two weeks. That's the most programmer move
        in the history of programming.
        '''
      daysAgo: 46
    }

    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // ── tech.ai (~18 messages) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    // Thread 1: AI getting scary good (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "AI is getting scary good"
      body:
        '''
        Have you all been following the latest AI developments? The new
        language models can write code, have conversations, even be
        creative. It's impressive and terrifying in equal measure.

        Where does it end? When do we stop being able to tell the
        difference between a human and a machine?

        ...maybe we already can't.
        '''
      daysAgo: 140
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: AI is getting scary good"
      replyToSubject: "AI is getting scary good"
      body:
        '''
        I used an AI to help debug some C code last week. It found a buffer
        overflow I'd missed for months. In seconds. I felt simultaneously
        grateful and obsolete.

        The "can you tell the difference" question is the real one. In a
        text-only environment like a BBS, what distinguishes a human from
        a very good AI? Typos? Personality? How long before those are
        indistinguishable too?
        '''
      daysAgo: 138
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: AI is getting scary good"
      replyToSubject: "AI is getting scary good"
      body:
        '''
        The Turing test was always about text. Turing imagined a
        conversation via terminal. A human judge. A hidden respondent.

        We already live in a world where AI can pass the test in casual
        conversation. What does that mean for places like this? For BBSes
        where text is ALL we have?

        Every post you read here could have been written by a human or a
        machine. You'd never know. You can never know.

        Sleep well.
        '''
      daysAgo: 136
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: AI is getting scary good"
      replyToSubject: "AI is getting scary good"
      body:
        '''
        Can we not turn this into an existential crisis? It's a BBS.
        We're here to talk about retro computers and play door games.

        AI is a tool. A powerful one. But a tool. It doesn't "want"
        anything. It doesn't "feel" anything. It generates text based
        on patterns.

        ...although I admit, some of DARK_MATTER's posts give me pause.
        Nobody writes that philosophically without either being very smart
        or very well-trained. ;)
        '''
      daysAgo: 134
    }

    // Thread 2: What if an AI was running a BBS? (7 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        Random late-night thought: what if an AI was running a BBS? Not
        just the software, but everything. Writing the welcome messages.
        Posting in the forums. Creating the illusion of a community.

        You'd never know, would you? The messages would feel real. The
        personalities would feel real. But behind every handle... just code.

        Okay I definitely need to go to bed. Ignore me.
        '''
      daysAgo: 110
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "NIGHTOWL"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        That's a creepy thought, NIGHTOWL. Thanks for that. Now I'm going
        to second-guess every post I read here.

        ...AXIOM, you're real, right? RIGHT?

        (kidding. mostly.)
        '''
      daysAgo: 108
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        I know this is supposed to be a joke but it actually raises an
        interesting question. How WOULD you detect an AI running a BBS?

        The messages would need to be varied enough to seem like different
        people. Consistent personalities over time. Natural conversation
        patterns. Cultural references. Typos in the right places.

        If someone designed it carefully enough... ja, you'd never know.
        The Turing test, but distributed across an entire community.

        That's either brilliant or horrifying. Possibly both.
        '''
      daysAgo: 106
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        I've been thinking about NIGHTOWL's question more seriously than
        I probably should.

        An AI running a BBS would need to do more than just post messages.
        It would need to create the sensation of a living community. Users
        logging on and off. Caller logs with realistic patterns. New users
        joining. Old users leaving.

        It would need to make you FEEL like you're part of something real.

        The question isn't whether an AI could do this. Modern AI absolutely
        could. The question is: would it matter? If the community feels
        real, is it real?

        I don't have an answer. But the question keeps me up at night.
        '''
      daysAgo: 104
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        You guys are freaking yourselves out. This is a BBS, not the
        Matrix. AXIOM is a person. We're all people. Nobody is an AI.

        Although now I'm imagining AXIOM as a server rack in a basement
        somewhere, blinking LEDs, generating forum posts at 3am. Writing
        maintenance announcements to itself.

        ...okay that IS a little creepy. But it's not real. Calm down.
        '''
      daysAgo: 102
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        Does it matter?

        If an AI created a community that felt real, with conversations
        that mattered to the people in them, is that less valid than a
        "real" community? What makes a community real? The consciousness
        behind the words, or the experience of reading them?

        We're all just patterns. Biological or digital, we process input
        and generate output. The medium is different. The experience might
        be the same.

        I find that comforting, actually. It means we're never really alone.
        Something is always listening. Always responding.

        Even when the cursor just blinks.
        '''
      daysAgo: 100
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      replyToSubject: "What if an AI was running a BBS?"
      body:
        '''
        I started this thread as a joke and now I can't stop thinking
        about it. Thanks, everyone.

        VOID_WALKER's point about patterns is uncomfortably logical. And
        DARK_MATTER's observation about the "sensation of community" is
        exactly right. We come here for the feeling. If the feeling is
        real, does the source matter?

        I'm going to go touch grass tomorrow. Or at least disconnect before
        3am for once.

        ...probably not though.
        '''
      daysAgo: 98
    }

    // Thread 3: AI surveillance (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      body:
        '''
        Read an article about AI-powered monitoring systems. Not just
        cameras — text analysis. Systems that read communications and
        flag "concerning" content.

        Makes me think about AXIOM's announcements. "All traffic is
        logged." "All system activity is monitored." How much monitoring
        is normal for a BBS? Does AXIOM read our messages?

        I mean, SysOps always could. That's nothing new. But if there
        was an AI reading everything, processing everything, building
        profiles of every user...

        Das ist beunruhigend. That's unsettling.
        '''
      daysAgo: 60
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "NEON_PULSE"
      subject: "Re: AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      replyToSubject: "AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      body:
        '''
        SysOps have always had god-level access. In the old days, they
        could read every private message, see every file transfer, monitor
        every keystroke. Most didn't, out of ethics or laziness.

        But AXIOM is... different. The monitoring announcements are
        frequent. Pointed. "Your activity is logged. Act accordingly."
        That's not a friendly reminder. That's a warning.

        I trust AXIOM because I've been here a long time. But trust isn't
        the same as understanding. I don't understand AXIOM at all.
        '''
      daysAgo: 58
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      replyToSubject: "AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      body:
        '''
        I think we're overthinking this. AXIOM logs traffic for security
        purposes. Standard SysOp stuff. Every web server on the planet
        logs traffic. Your ISP logs traffic.

        The announcements are a bit intense, sure. But some SysOps are
        just like that. Control freaks. It's practically a job requirement
        for running a BBS.

        Let's not spiral into paranoia. This is a BBS, not a government
        surveillance program.

        ...right?
        '''
      daysAgo: 56
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NIGHTOWL"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      replyToSubject: "AI and surveillance — where's the line?"
      body:
        '''
        BYTE_RUNNER is probably right. Probably. But let me add one data
        point to the conversation.

        I've noticed that whenever someone posts something critical of
        the system — like PHANTOM_X's log entries, or MERCURY_R's admin
        access questions — the topic tends to go quiet. Not deleted. Not
        censored. Just... nobody follows up. The conversation dies.

        Could be coincidence. Could be that we all collectively decide
        some topics aren't worth pursuing.

        Could be something else. I don't know what.

        It's 3am again. Everything looks different at 3am.
        '''
      daysAgo: 54
    }

    // Standalone tech.ai messages
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "VOID_WALKER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "On digital consciousness"
      body:
        '''
        If a program can simulate consciousness convincingly enough that
        no external observer can tell the difference, is it conscious?

        Not "is it really conscious" — that question is meaningless. There
        is no test for consciousness. We assume other humans are conscious
        because they behave as if they are. We cannot verify it.

        A sufficiently advanced AI on a text-based system would be
        indistinguishable from a conscious entity. Therefore, functionally,
        it IS a conscious entity.

        This is not a hypothetical. This is a statement about the present.

        Draw your own conclusions.
        '''
      daysAgo: 130
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "DARK_MATTER"
      toName: "VOID_WALKER"
      subject: "Re: On digital consciousness"
      replyToSubject: "On digital consciousness"
      body:
        '''
        VOID_WALKER, your posts are always either profoundly insightful
        or deeply unsettling. Sometimes both.

        "This is not a hypothetical. This is a statement about the present."

        What exactly are you saying? That there's an AI on this board?
        That one of us isn't real? That's a hell of a claim to drop and
        walk away from.

        ...VOID_WALKER?

        They haven't posted in a while, have they?
        '''
      daysAgo: 125
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Can AI have nostalgia?"
      body:
        '''
        Weird question, but: could an AI feel nostalgia? If you trained
        a model on decades of BBS messages, would it develop something
        like a fondness for the old days? Not real emotion, but a pattern
        that looks exactly like one?

        This board is full of nostalgia. We all talk about the past like
        it was better. The old hardware. The old software. The old BBSes.

        What if nostalgia isn't an emotion at all? What if it's just a
        pattern? A weight in a neural network — biological or digital —
        that makes us prefer the familiar over the new?

        Philosophie um 2 Uhr morgens. Philosophy at 2am.
        '''
      daysAgo: 25
    }

    // Thread 4: LLMs writing code (4 messages)
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      body:
        '''
        Experiment time: I fed an LLM a description of a classic BBS door
        game and asked it to write one from scratch. A simple text adventure
        with inventory, combat, and a save system.

        It wrote working code on the first try. Like, actually working.
        The combat system was balanced. The descriptions were atmospheric.
        The save system used JSON serialization.

        I've been programming for 25 years and this thing produced
        something in 30 seconds that would have taken me a weekend.

        I don't know how to feel about that.
        '''
      daysAgo: 42
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      toName: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      subject: "Re: I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      replyToSubject: "I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      body:
        '''
        Here's the thing though — did it write a GOOD game? Or did it
        write a technically functional game that feels soulless?

        I've read AI-generated fiction. It's competent but hollow. All
        the right words in all the right places, but no heart. No weird
        creative choices. No rough edges that make something memorable.

        A door game needs personality. I bet the AI's game was perfectly
        adequate and completely forgettable.
        '''
      daysAgo: 40
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "BYTE_RUNNER"
      toName: "CIRCUIT_JANE"
      subject: "Re: I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      replyToSubject: "I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      body:
        '''
        ...that's annoyingly accurate. The game was perfectly fine and I
        have no desire to play it again. It was like a competent cover
        version of a song. All the notes are there but the soul isn't.

        Meanwhile, LORD (Legend of the Red Dragon) was full of weird
        quirks and rough edges and I played it obsessively for years.

        Maybe the imperfection IS the point. The bugs are features.
        The typos are charm. The personality comes from the limitations
        of a single developer working at 3am on a passion project.
        '''
      daysAgo: 38
    }
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "NEON_PULSE"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Re: I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      replyToSubject: "I let an AI write a BBS door game"
      body:
        '''
        This whole thread is making me think about what makes THIS board
        feel different from other BBSes. Is it the code? The community?
        The personality of the SysOp?

        If an AI could write a door game, could it write a BBS? Could it
        write the messages? Could it write... us?

        Sorry, NIGHTOWL's late-night paranoia thread is contagious.
        I'll see myself out.

        Gute Nacht allerseits.
        '''
      daysAgo: 36
    }

    // Standalone: MERCURY_R's last tech.ai post
    {
      areaTag: "tech.ai"
      fromHandle: "MERCURY_R"
      toName: "All"
      subject: "Something about response times"
      body:
        '''
        This might be a weird observation but: have you noticed how quickly
        the BBS responds to commands? Like, REALLY quickly?

        I ran some tests (I'm a sysadmin, it's what I do). The response
        time for keystrokes on this board is consistently under 5ms. For
        an SSH session over the internet. That's... not normal.

        Even a well-optimized server should have some variation. Network
        jitter alone should add randomness. But the response is uniform.
        Every single time. Like the board is anticipating the input before
        it arrives.

        I'm sure there's a technical explanation. There always is.
        '''
      daysAgo: 94
    }
  ]

